              "comments": {
                "nodes": [
                  {
                    "id": "PRRC_kwDOFcwZ1c5y13f1",
                    "body": "It sounds to me that all of these should be true for left ideals as well thanks to the commutation hypotheses, right? I recognize it's a bit unsatisfying to be able to state them for left ideals but not right ideals, but I think it would still be better not to restrict to two-sided ideals.",
                    "createdAt": "2025-01-23T10:17:55Z",
                    "author": {
                      "login": "ADedecker"
                    }
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "PRRC_kwDOFcwZ1c5y2EH8",
                    "body": "Yeah, it seems you're right.",
                    "createdAt": "2025-01-23T10:51:32Z",
                    "author": {
                      "login": "AntoineChambert-Loir"
                    }
                  },
                  {
                    "id": "PRRC_kwDOFcwZ1c5y2HOU",
                    "body": "On the other hand, having this for ideals requires to generalize (it is often trivial) lemmas from `CommSemiring` to `Semiring` in much earlier files of the library. So I believe I'll delete the noncommutative case.",
